BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:gVvbc9hirOgBk04GZRXzI
SUMMARY:Behavioral Acculturation and Acculturative Stress in Latino Immigra
	nt Youth: The Moderating Role of Perceived Autonomy
DTSTAMP:20260625T012301Z
DTSTART:20260626T153000Z
DESCRIPTION:&#160\;  Speaker: Valentina Maza  Masters Candidate  Thesis Def
	ense  Department: Psychology  Latino immigrant youth represent a rapidly g
	rowing demographic in the United States\, facing unique socio-ecological d
	emands as they navigate the post-migration landscape. While research has e
	xtensively examined post-migration stressors\, the psychological condition
	s surrounding the pre-migration phase remain underexplored. This study inv
	estigated the relationship between behavioral acculturation and acculturat
	ive stress among recently immigrated Latino youth and examined whether per
	ceived autonomy in the migration moderates this association.  Utilizing a 
	mixed-methods design\, data were analyzed from a sample of 90 Latino youth
	 (ages 15–25\, M = 19.72) recruited from a specialized public high school 
	for recent immigrants in Houston\, Texas. Participants completed the Short
	 Acculturation Scale for Hispanics (SASH)\, the Societal\, Attitudinal\, F
	amilial\, and Environmental Acculturative Stress Scale for Children (SAFE-
	C)\, and the semi-structured Migration Experiences Interview (MEI).  Hiera
	rchical multiple regression analyses revealed that behavioral acculturatio
	n did not significantly predict acculturative stress\, and the hypothesize
	d moderation effect of perceived autonomy was not supported (p = .411). Ho
	wever\, participant gender emerged as a powerful\, persistent independent 
	predictor of acculturative stress (B = 9.577\, p = .027)\, with female you
	th reporting significantly higher stress levels (M = 42.03) than their mal
	e peers (M = 32.65).  &#160\;  (Department : Psychology)\n\nhttps://events
	.rice.edu/event/432837-behavioral-acculturation-and-acculturative-stress\n
	\nFrom Rice University - Open to the Public
URL:https://events.rice.edu/event/432837-behavioral-acculturation-and-accul
	turative-stress
GEO:29.7174;-95.4018
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:rice-public-events
CATEGORIES:Rice University - Open to the Public
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT1H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:JYSamhHcR8hTrpYky3VSI
SUMMARY:Exploring Organic Transformations with a Photocatalytic Twist
DTSTAMP:20260625T012301Z
DTSTART:20260626T153000Z
DESCRIPTION:&#160\;  Speaker: Michael Yasuda  Masters Candidate  Thesis Def
	ense  Department: Chemistry  Location: BioScience Research Collaborative 8
	01  The use of metal catalysis has revolutionized synthesis of important m
	olecules including natural products\, pharmaceuticals\, and petrochemicals
	. While synthetic chemists have made great strides in understanding what m
	etal catalysis can offer\, both in terms of mechanistic understanding and 
	possible reactions\, these advances have been most notable for noble metal
	s such as palladium and rhodium. By contrast\, the catalytic use and mecha
	nistic understanding of economical and earth abundant metals remains relat
	ively underdeveloped\, hampering the effective use of these promising spec
	ies in synthesis. Herein\, efforts towards understanding the potential of 
	Earth abundant metals to achieve useful synthetic transformations and hypo
	thesis-driven fundamental study of their underlying mechanisms is disclose
	d. First\, contributions towards a cobalt-catalyzed epoxide rearrangement 
	with complementary selectivity to the Meinwald rearrangement\, furnishing 
	ketone products\, is investigated. In a parallel study\, mechanistic work 
	towards understanding an iron-photocatalyzed decarboxylative addition acro
	ss bicyclo[1.1.0]butanes (BCB)\, establishing the radical character of the
	 reaction and identifying the rate determining character of the addition s
	tep via kinetic isotope effect (KIE) study\, is shown. Finally\, prelimina
	ry efforts towards using tetrabutylammonium decatungstate (TBADT) as a pho
	tocatalyst for various transformations is reported\, including forming acy
	l azides from aldehydes.  &#160\;  https://riceuniversity.zoom.us/j/954077
	97129?pwd=1LTPids9WkwaUEXK8g6RFrhavaEaHR.1  Meeting ID: 954 0779 7129  Pas
	scode: 482061  (Department : Chemistry)\n\nhttps://events.rice.edu/live/ev
	ents/432746-exploring-organic-transformations-with-a\n\nFrom Rice Universi
	ty - Open to the Public
URL:https://events.rice.edu/live/events/432746-exploring-organic-transforma
	tions-with-a
GEO:29.7174;-95.4018
LOCATION:BioScience Research Collaborative
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:rice-public-events
CATEGORIES:Rice University - Open to the Public
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT1H
END:VEVENT
